## Setup

My preference is to use Gitbash in my terminal, and these commands work in gitbash. I believe the default is powershell and I'm totally okay with you using that, you'll just need to google the terminal commands for that

To create a terminal, go to the top left of the screen and click Terminal -> New Terminal. To create a gitbash session, hover over the terminal, go to the top right of it where you see the **+** and click the down arrow next to it. then, hit Gitbash. 

### 1. Create a Branch

Remember, this will branch off of main and allow you to make edits without it affecting the main stream of code
```bash
git checkout -b aerodynamics-Week-4-your-name
```
Once you're in your branch, create a folder called your_name with a script week_4_training_your_name.py inside of it and copy/paste the code from aerosandbox_training.py inside of the python script.

### 2. Create a Virtual Environment

This is an isolated python environment for your project that can hold all of the packages you need (in this case, aerosandbox). The command has you install in python 3.14, which you should probably have honestly just to have the most up-to-date version. If you need to install python, do it from python.org (not the Microsoft store).
```bash
py -3.14 -m venv .venv
```

### 3. Activate the Virtual Environment

Now that you've made the virtual environment (venv), you need to activate it
```bash
source .venv/Scripts/activate
```

You should see `(.venv)` appear in your terminal prompt.

### 4. Install AeroSandbox

This actually installs the module onto your venv for you to use. While python comes preinstalled with lots of modules (math, pathlib, os, typing, etc.), there are lots of free, open-source modules to download
```bash
pip install aerosandbox[full]
```
The [full] command basically tells pip to install everything, as aerosandbox has an option to not install all aspects. For more instructions and background information about what's happening, visit https://peterdsharpe.github.io/AeroSandbox/. 

